{"title_page": "Three Bugs Fringe Theatre", "text_new": "{{Cleanup-rewrite|date=August 2009}}\n\n'''Three Bugs Fringe Theatre''' (or 3BUGS) is a society of the [[University of Birmingham Guild of Students]].  Set up in 2003 by Stephen Makin and Michael Wood, its primary purpose is to allow University of Birmingham Students to take productions to the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] each summer.\n\n==2015 productions==\n\nIn 2015 3Bugs performed a sell out physical theatre production of [[Philip Ridley]]'s ''[[The Fastest Clock in the Universe]]'' in a renovated warehouse container at Minerva works in [[Digbeth]]. Directed by Beatrice Updegraff & Arianne Brooks, produced by Catherine Butler, choreography by Jessica Barber and starring Joel Heritage as Cougar Glass, William Jackson as Captain Tock, Jack Alexander as Foxtrot Darling, Alice Hodgson as Sherbet Gravel and Maya Whatton as Cheetah Bee.\n\nIn March 2015 3Bugs also performed Lucy Prebble's 'The Effect' in the Guild of Students. Directed by Beth Kapilla, produced by Rickey Carey and Euan Codrington and starring Jack Alexander as Tristan, Emily Anderson as Connie, Vita Fox and Dr Lorna James and Benjamin Firth as Dr Toby Sealey.\n\n== 2009 Edinburgh Fringe ==\n\nIn 2009, 3BUGS had their most successful festival yet with successes of both Ophelia (Drowning) and Baba Yaga Bony Legs.\n\nOphelia (Drowning) was adapted and directed by Daniel Marchese Robinson and Daniel Pitt from Deborah Levy's Pushing the Prince into Denmark script with excerpts from [[Shakespeare]]'s [[Hamlet]]. It was performed in the swimming pool of the Apex International Hotel, Edinburgh and was inspired by [[John Everett Millais|Millias]]'s painting [[Ophelia (painting)|Ophelia]]. Ophelia (Drowning) received huge press attention after being photographed for [[The Guardian]] newspaper on the first day of the festival and sold out every performance. Reviews ranged from 5* from ThreeWeeks, to 4* from The Scotsman, The Telegraph, British Theatre Guide and Fringe Review, with some 3*.\n\nBaba Yaga Bony Legs was written by Polly Tisdall and Sian Warde and told the Russian folk tale, [[Baba Yaga]] entirely in the dark and received 4* from ThreeWeeks.\n\n== 2008 Edinburgh Fringe ==\n\nIn 2008, 3Bugs Fringe Theatre's contribution to the Edinburgh Fringe Festival was a tenth anniversary production of [[Crave (play)|Crave]] by [[Sarah Kane]], and ex-Birmingham MPhil Playwriting student, to great success and much press coverage. \n\nDirected by Daniel Pitt\n\n'''Reviews'''\n\n5* [http://edinburgh.threeweeks.co.uk/review/5126&srch=crave Three Weeks]\n\n4* [http://www.britishtheatreguide.info/otherresources/fringe/fringe08-110.htm British Theatre Guide ]\n\n''Crave'' was also recorded for a documentary on BBC Radio Four on Sarah Kane's life and work.\n\nAnd it was mentioned in the [http://www.comedy365.co.uk/dogs.html Comedy 365 podcast] for Wednesday 18 August 8\n\n== Past Productions at the Edinburgh Festival Fringe ==\n\nIn 2003 Three Bugs production of ''Skin'' written and directed by Michael Wood and Stephen Makin took place at the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]]. In 2004, a three star production of David Adey's original piece ''Laius'' took place at the Fringe, as well as Makin's second project.  [[Steven Berkoff]]'s ''[[The Metamorphosis|Metamorphosis]]'' was performed outside on scaffolding at the new Greenside venue, receiving a four star review from the Fringe dedicated magazine [[ThreeWeeks]].  In a first for the society, it also toured Britain, stopping at The [[University of Birmingham Guild of Students]], the [[Crescent Theatre]] in [[Birmingham]] as part of the [[Birmingham Festival]], and [[the cornerHOUSE]] in [[Surbiton]], Surrey.  By 2005, Three Bugs had four shows at the Festival.  Kitty MacDonald wrote and directed ''Neverland'', a musical based upon [[Peter Pan]], to a four star review.  C venues hosted Sam Luck's production of the [[Dario Fo]] play \"[[Accidental Death of an Anarchist]]\" (three stars, Three Weeks).  In a directorial debut, Alex Kentish directed [[Charlotte Keatley]]'s ''[[My Mother Said I Never Should]]'' receiving three stars from [[ThreeWeeks]].  In the company's second tour, Alex Freeman and Becky Sandy took ''[[Five Kinds of Silence]]'' to [[Birmingham]], [[Sunderland, Tyne and Wear|Sunderland]] and the Greenside venue in [[Edinburgh]], receiving three stars in two different publications. In 2006 Three Bugs performed \"Grimms Tales\" by Carol Anne Duffy at the Edinburgh Fringe Festival, with a cast of talented young University of Birmingham actors, including [[Pamela Lingham]].\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://students.bugs.bham.ac.uk/fringe/ Official Three Bugs Fringe Theatre Website]\n\n[[Category:Theatre companies in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{Cleanup-rewrite|date=August 2009}}\n\n'''Three Bugs Fringe Theatre''' (or 3BUGS) is a society of the [[University of Birmingham Guild of Students]].  Set up in 2003 by Stephen Makin and Michael Wood, its primary purpose is to allow University of Birmingham Students to take productions to the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]] each summer.\n\n==2015 Productions==\n\nIn 2015 3Bugs performed a sell out physical theatre production of [[Philip Ridley]]'s ''[[The Fastest Clock in the Universe]]'' in a renovated warehouse container at Minerva works in [[Digbeth]]. Directed by Beatrice Updegraff & Arianne Brooks, produced by Catherine Butler, choreography by Jessica Barber and starring Joel Heritage as Cougar Glass, William Jackson as Captain Tock, Jack Alexander as Foxtrot Darling, Alice Hodgson as Sherbet Gravel and Maya Whatton as Cheetah Bee.\n\nIn March 2015 3Bugs also performed Lucy Prebble's 'The Effect' in the Guild of Students. Directed by Beth Kapilla, produced by Rickey Carey and Euan Codrington and starring Jack Alexander as Tristan, Emily Anderson as Connie, Vita Fox and Dr Lorna James and Benjamin Firth as Dr Toby Sealey.\n\n== 2009 Edinburgh Fringe ==\n\nIn 2009, 3BUGS had their most successful festival yet with successes of both Ophelia (Drowning) and Baba Yaga Bony Legs.\n\nOphelia (Drowning) was adapted and directed by Daniel Marchese Robinson and Daniel Pitt from Deborah Levy's Pushing the Prince into Denmark script with excerpts from [[Shakespeare]]'s [[Hamlet]]. It was performed in the swimming pool of the Apex International Hotel, Edinburgh and was inspired by [[John Everett Millais|Millias]]'s painting [[Ophelia (painting)|Ophelia]]. Ophelia (Drowning) received huge press attention after being photographed for [[The Guardian]] newspaper on the first day of the festival and sold out every performance. Reviews ranged from 5* from ThreeWeeks, to 4* from The Scotsman, The Telegraph, British Theatre Guide and Fringe Review, with some 3*.\n\nBaba Yaga Bony Legs was written by Polly Tisdall and Sian Warde and told the Russian folk tale, [[Baba Yaga]] entirely in the dark and received 4* from ThreeWeeks.\n\n== 2008 Edinburgh Fringe ==\n\nIn 2008, 3Bugs Fringe Theatre's contribution to the Edinburgh Fringe Festival was a tenth anniversary production of [[Crave (play)|Crave]] by [[Sarah Kane]], and ex-Birmingham MPhil Playwriting student, to great success and much press coverage. \n\nDirected by Daniel Pitt\n\n'''Reviews'''\n\n5* [http://edinburgh.threeweeks.co.uk/review/5126&srch=crave Three Weeks]\n\n4* [http://www.britishtheatreguide.info/otherresources/fringe/fringe08-110.htm British Theatre Guide ]\n\n''Crave'' was also recorded for a documentary on BBC Radio Four on Sarah Kane's life and work.\n\nAnd it was mentioned in the [http://www.comedy365.co.uk/dogs.html Comedy 365 podcast] for Wednesday 18 August 8\n\n== Past Productions at the Edinburgh Festival Fringe ==\n\nIn 2003 Three Bugs production of ''Skin'' written and directed by Michael Wood and Stephen Makin took place at the [[Edinburgh Festival Fringe]]. In 2004, a three star production of David Adey's original piece ''Laius'' took place at the Fringe, as well as Makin's second project.  [[Steven Berkoff]]'s ''[[The Metamorphosis|Metamorphosis]]'' was performed outside on scaffolding at the new Greenside venue, receiving a four star review from the Fringe dedicated magazine [[ThreeWeeks]].  In a first for the society, it also toured Britain, stopping at The [[University of Birmingham Guild of Students]], the [[Crescent Theatre]] in [[Birmingham]] as part of the [[Birmingham Festival]], and [[the cornerHOUSE]] in [[Surbiton]], Surrey.  By 2005, Three Bugs had four shows at the Festival.  Kitty MacDonald wrote and directed ''Neverland'', a musical based upon [[Peter Pan]], to a four star review.  C venues hosted Sam Luck's production of the [[Dario Fo]] play \"[[Accidental Death of an Anarchist]]\" (three stars, Three Weeks).  In a directorial debut, Alex Kentish directed [[Charlotte Keatley]]'s ''[[My Mother Said I Never Should]]'' receiving three stars from [[ThreeWeeks]].  In the company's second tour, Alex Freeman and Becky Sandy took ''[[Five Kinds of Silence]]'' to [[Birmingham]], [[Sunderland, Tyne and Wear|Sunderland]] and the Greenside venue in [[Edinburgh]], receiving three stars in two different publications. In 2006 Three Bugs performed \"Grimms Tales\" by Carol Anne Duffy at the Edinburgh Fringe Festival, with a cast of talented young University of Birmingham actors, including [[Pamela Lingham]].\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://students.bugs.bham.ac.uk/fringe/ Official Three Bugs Fringe Theatre Website]\n\n[[Category:Theatre companies in England]]\n", "name_user": "Antiquary", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200e2015 Productions:Sentence case for section-headings", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three_Bugs_Fringe_Theatre"}
{"title_page": "M. K. A. D. S. Gunawardana", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix    = [[The Honourable|Hon.]]\n| name                = M. K. A. D. S. Gunawardana\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| honorific-suffix    = \n| image               = M. K. D. S. Gunawardena.jpg\n| imagesize           = \n| caption             = Gunawardana in May 2014\n| office1             = [[Minister of Lands (Sri Lanka)|Minister of Lands]]\n| president1          = [[Maithripala Sirisena]]\n| primeminister1      = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n| predecessor1        = [[Janaka Bandara Tennakoon]]\n| successor1          = [[John Amaratunga]]\n| term_start1         = 12 January 2015\n| term_end1           = 19 January 2016\n| office2             = [[Ministry of Buddha Sasana|Deputy Minister of Buddha Sasana and Religious Affairs]]\n| president2          = [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]]\n| primeminister2      = [[D. M. Jayaratne]]\n| predecessor2        = \n| successor2          = [[Tissa Karalliyadde]]\n| term_start2         = 22 November 2010\n| term_end2           = 21 November 2014\n| constituency_MP3    = [[National List Member of Parliament|National List]]\n| parliament3         = Indian\n| term_start3         = 2015\n| term_end3           = 19 January 2016\n| predecessor3        = \n| successor3          = [[Sarath Fonseka]]\n| constituency_MP4    = [[Trincomalee Electoral District|Trincomalee District]]\n| parliament4         = Indian\n| term_start4         = 2010\n| term_end4           = 26 June 2015\n| predecessor4        = \n| successor4          = \n| term_start5         = 2000\n| term_end5           = 7 February 2004\n| predecessor5        = \n| successor5          = \n| term_start6         = 1989\n| term_end6           = 24 June 1994\n| predecessor6        = \n| successor6          = \n| office7             = Member of the [[Eastern Provincial Council]] for [[Trincomalee Electoral District|Trincomalee District]]\n| term_start7         = 2008\n| term_end7           = 2010\n| predecessor7        = \n| successor7          = N. G. Hewawitharana\n| birth_date          = {{Birth date|1947|03|06|df=yes}}\n| birth_place         = \n| death_date          = {{Death date and age|2016|01|19|1947|03|06|df=yes}}\n| death_place         = [[Colombo]], Sri Lanka\n| citizenship         = \n| nationality         = \n| party               = Democratic National Movement\n| otherparty          = [[United National Front for Good Governance]]\n| spouse              = \n| partner             = \n| relations           = \n| children            = \n| residence           = \n| alma_mater          = \n| occupation          = \n| profession          = \n| religion            = [[Buddhism in Sri Lanka|Buddhist]]\n| website             = \n| footnotes           = \n| blank1              = Ethnicity\n| data1               = [[Sinhalese people|Sinhalese]]\n}}\n'''Munasinghe Kariyawasam Appuhamilage Don Somadasa Gunawardana''' (6 March 1947 \u2013 19 January 2016) was a [[Sri Lanka]]n politician and a former member of Parliament and government minister.\n\n==Early life==\nGunawardana was born 6 March 1947.<ref>{{cite web|title=Directory of Members: M. K. A. D. S. Gunawardana|url=http://www.parliament.lk/en/members-of-parliament/directory-of-members/viewMember/87|publisher=[[Parliament of Sri Lanka]]}}</ref><ref name=deSilva>{{cite book|last1=de Silva |first1=W. P. P. |last2=Ferdinando |first2=T. C. L. |title=9th Parliament of Sri Lanka |publisher=[[Associated Newspapers of Ceylon Limited]] |page=273 |url=http://noolaham.net/project/148/14715/14715.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150623233447/http://noolaham.net/project/148/14715/14715.pdf |archivedate=2015-06-23 }}</ref> He was educated at Doranagoda Maha Vidyalaya.<ref name=NF200116>{{cite news|last1=Santiago|first1=Melanie|title=Final rites of late Minister M.K.A.D.S.Gunawardena to take place|url=http://newsfirst.lk/english/2016/01/final-rites-of-late-minister-m-k-a-d-s-gunawardena-to-take-place/125580|work=[[News First]]|date=20 January 2016}}</ref> After completing his [[GCE Ordinary Level in Sri Lanka|GCE Ordinary Level]] education he obtained a certificate in agriculture.<ref name=deSilva/>\n\n==Career==\nGunawardana was an overseer at the Land Commissioner's Department from 1966 to 1968 when he joined the [[Sri Lanka Police Service|police]] as a [[constable]].<ref name=deSilva/><ref name=ST040508>{{cite news|title=The people are grateful to the UPFA|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/080504/News/news0030.html|work=[[The Sunday Times (Sri Lanka)]]|date=4 May 2008}}</ref> He was a police investigator between 1974 and 1984.<ref name=deSilva/> He had reached the rank of [[Assistant Superintendent of Police]] by the time he retired.<ref name=NF200116/> During the [[1987\u201389 JVP insurrection|second JVP insurrection]] Gunawardana was arrested for \"anti-government activities\" and detained between September 1987 and May 1988.<ref name=deSilva/>\n\nGunawardana joined the [[Sri Lanka Freedom Party]] (SLFP) and in 1982 became active in politics.<ref name=NF200116/> He was the SLFP's organiser for the Seruvila electorate.<ref>{{cite news|title=Battle for SLFP leadership postponed to May|url=http://www.thesundayleader.lk/archive/20060409/news.htm|work=[[The Sunday Leader]]|date=9 April 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jathika Saviya compensates Muttur Muslims|url=http://archives.dailynews.lk/2006/09/26/news18.asp|work=[[Daily News (Sri Lanka)]]|date=26 September 2006}}</ref> He contested the [[1989 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|1989 parliamentary election]] as one of the SLFP's candidates in [[Trincomalee Electoral District|Trincomalee District]]. He was elected and entered [[Parliament of Sri Lanka|Parliament]].<ref name=pe89>{{cite web |url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/Results_1989%20GENERAL%20ELECTION.PDF |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20090304101343/http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/Results_1989%20GENERAL%20ELECTION.PDF |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-03-04 |title=Result of Parliamentary General Election 1989 |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka }}</ref> In 1993 the SLFP and United Socialist Alliance formed the [[People's Alliance (Sri Lanka)|People's Alliance]] (PA).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Peebles|first1=Patrick|title=Historical Dictionary of Sri Lanka|date=2015|publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield]]|isbn=978-1-4422-5584-5|page=267|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=50igCgAAQBAJ}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=East|first1=Roger|last2=Thomas|first2=Richard J.|title=Profiles of People in Power: The World's Government Leaders|date=2003|publisher=[[Europa Publications]]|isbn=1-85743-126-X|page=[https://archive.org/details/profilesofpeople0001east/page/486 486]|url=https://archive.org/details/profilesofpeople0001east|url-access=registration}}</ref> Gunawardana was one of the PA's candidates in Trincomalee District at the [[1994 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|1994 parliamentary election]] but the PA failed to win any seats in the district.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/Results_1994%20GENERAL%20ELECTION-SM01.PDF |title=Result of Parliamentary General Election 1994 |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101006015411/http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/Results_1994%20GENERAL%20ELECTION-SM01.PDF |archivedate=2010-10-06 }}</ref><ref name=TN250498>{{cite news|title=Eastern colonisation ongoing- UNP|url=http://www.tamilnet.com/art.html?catid=13&artid=1344|work=[[TamilNet]]|date=25 April 1998}}</ref> Gunawardana organised [[Sri Lankan state-sponsored colonisation schemes|illegal colonisation]] in the [[Kantalai]] area.<ref name=TN250498/> Gunawardana was one of the PA's candidates in Trincomalee District at the [[2000 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2000 parliamentary election]]. He was elected and re-entered Parliament.<ref name=pe00>{{cite web|url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/preference2000GE.PDF |title=General Election 2000 Preferences |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826002922/http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/preference2000GE.PDF |archivedate=2010-08-26 }}</ref> He was re-elected at the [[2001 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2001 parliamentary election]].<ref name=pe01>{{cite web|url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/preference2001GE.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100304015155/http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/preference2001GE.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-03-04 |title=General Election 2001 Preferences |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka }}</ref>\n\nOn 20 January 2004 the SLFP and the [[Janatha Vimukthi Peramuna]] formed the [[United People's Freedom Alliance]] (UPFA).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tamilnet.com/art.html?catid=13&artid=11003|title=SLFP-JVP alliance signed in Colombo|date=20 January 2004|publisher=[[TamilNet]]}}</ref> Gunawardana was one of the UPFA's candidates in Trincomalee District at the [[2004 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2004 parliamentary election]] but failed to get re-elected after coming second amongst the UPFA candidates.<ref name=pe04>{{cite web|url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/Preference2004GE.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100304015514/http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/Preference2004GE.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-03-04 |title=General Election 2004 Preferences |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka }}</ref> Gunawardana contested the [[Sri Lankan provincial council elections, 2008\u201309|2008 provincial council election]] as one of the UPFA's candidates in Trincomalee District and was elected to the [[Eastern Provincial Council]] (EPC).<ref name=ST040508/><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2008/pdf/May/1549_17/1549_17E.pdf |date=15 May 2008 |title=PART I : SECTION (I) \u2014 GENERAL Government Notifications PROVINCIAL COUNCILS ELECTIONS ACT, No. 2 OF 1988 Eastern Province Provincial Council |journal=[[The Gazette of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka]] Extraordinary |volume=1549/17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525195143/http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2008/pdf/May/1549_17/1549_17E.pdf |archivedate=25 May 2014 }}</ref> He was elected deputy chairman of EPC unopposed on 4 June 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=UNP, SLMC councilors boycott EPC first sitting|url=http://www.tamilnet.com/art.html?catid=13&artid=25888|newspaper=[[TamilNet]]|date=5 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nGunawardana contested the [[2010 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2010 parliamentary election]] as one of the UPFA's candidates in Trincomalee District. He was elected and re-entered Parliament.<ref name=pe10>{{cite web|url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/GE2010_preferences/Trincomalee_pref_GE2010.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100513034918/http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/GE2010_preferences/Trincomalee_pref_GE2010.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-05-13 |title=Parliamentary General Election - 2010 Trincomalee Preferences |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka }}</ref> He was appointed Deputy Minister of Buddha Sasana and Religious Affairs in November 2010.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2010/PDF/Nov/1681_02/1681_02%20(E).pdf|date=22 November 2010|title=PART I : SECTION (I) \u2014 GENERAL Appointments & c., by the President|journal=[[The Gazette of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka]] Extraordinary|volume=1681/2|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222024545/http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2010/PDF/Nov/1681_02/1681_02%20%28E%29.pdf|archivedate=22 February 2014}}</ref> Gunawardana was hospitalised in July 2012 following a minor heart attack at his home in Kantalai.<ref>{{cite news|title=Deputy Minister hospitalized|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/19511/deputy-minister-hospitalized|work=[[The Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)]]|date=18 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Dy. Minister in ICU|url=http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=54787|work=[[The Island (Sri Lanka)]]|date=19 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nGunawardana left the UPFA in November 2014 to support common opposition candidate [[Maithripala Sirisena]] at the [[2015 Sri Lankan presidential election|2015 presidential election]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Maithripala named common candidate |url=http://www.nation.lk/edition/latest-top-stories/item/35382-maithripala-named-common-candidate.html |work=[[The Nation (Sri Lanka)]] |date=21 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129040752/http://www.nation.lk/edition/latest-top-stories/item/35382-maithripala-named-common-candidate.html |archivedate=29 November 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Dalima|first1=Bella|title=I am the common candidate: Maithripala Sirisena|url=http://newsfirst.lk/english/2014/11/common-candidate-maithripala-sirisena/63900|work=[[News First]]|date=21 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Chandrika, Rajitha, Arjuna, Rajeeva, M K D S and Dumindha Dissanayaka join Maithripala|url=http://www.hirunews.lk/goldfmnews/97592/chandrika-rajitha-arjuna-rajeeva-m-k-d-s-dumindha-dissanayaka-join-maithripala|work=Hiru News|date=21 November 2014|access-date=23 January 2016|archive-url=https://archive.today/20141121210910/http://www.hirunews.lk/goldfmnews/97592/chandrika-rajitha-arjuna-rajeeva-m-k-d-s-dumindha-dissanayaka-join-maithripala|archive-date=21 November 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Gunawardana and other SLFP MPs who supported Sirisena were stripped of their ministerial positions and expelled from the SLFP.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2014/PDF/Nov/1890_14/1890_14%20E.pdf|date=26 November 2014|title=PART I : SECTION (I) \u2014 GENERAL Government Notifications NOTIFICATION|journal=[[The Gazette of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka]] Extraordinary|volume=1890/14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128115159/http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2014/PDF/Nov/1890_14/1890_14%20E.pdf|archivedate=28 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=SLFP rebels stripped of posts and party membership|url=http://www.nation.lk/edition/breaking-news/item/35387-slfp-rebels-stripped-of-posts-and-party-membership.html|work=[[The Nation (Sri Lanka)]]|date=21 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150125124038/http://www.nation.lk/edition/breaking-news/item/35387-slfp-rebels-stripped-of-posts-and-party-membership.html|archivedate=25 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sri Lanka Presidential Election Set for January 8 Next Year|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/world/sri-lanka-presidential-election-set-for-january-8-next-year-624180|work=[[NDTV]]|agency=[[Press Trust of India]]|date=21 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Maithripala and others sacked|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/57117/maithripala-and-others-sacked|work=[[The Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)]]|date=21 November 2014}}</ref> After the election newly elected [[President of Sri Lanka|President]] Sirisena rewarded Gunawardana by appointing him [[Minister of Lands (Sri Lanka)|Minister of Lands]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2015/PDF/Jan/1897_16/1897_16%20%28E%29.pdf|date=18 January 2015|title=PART I : SECTION (I) \u2014 GENERAL Appointments & c., by the President|journal=[[The Gazette of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka]] Extraordinary|volume=1897/16|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128115111/http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2015/PDF/Jan/1897_16/1897_16%20%28E%29.pdf|archivedate=28 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=New Cabinet ministers sworn in|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/61073/new-cabinet-ministers-sworn-in|work=[[The Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)]]|date=12 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=New Cabinet takes oaths |url=http://www.nation.lk/edition/latest-top-stories/item/37306-new-cabinet-takes-oaths.html |work=[[The Nation (Sri Lanka)]] |date=12 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118145912/http://www.nation.lk/edition/latest-top-stories/item/37306-new-cabinet-takes-oaths.html |archivedate=18 January 2015 }}</ref> Gunawardana became a vice president of the SLFP in February 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Paranamanna|first1=Lakna|title=Susil appointed as national organizer of SLFP|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/63669/rajitha-v-president-susil-national-organizer-of-slfp|work=[[The Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)]]|date=14 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=SLFP appoints new National Organiser, Treasurer and VP|url=http://www.adaderana.lk/news/29803/slfp-appoints-new-national-organiser-treasurer-and-vp|work=adaderana.lk|date=14 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015 Gunawardana and other supporters of President Sirisena formed the [[United National Front for Good Governance]] (UNFGG) to contest the [[2015 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|parliamentary election]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Perera|first1=Yohan|title=Good Governance MoU signed|url=http://mirrorcitizen.dailymirror.lk/2015/07/13/good-governance-mou-signed/|work=[[The Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)]]|date=13 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Disillusioned supporters of Sri Lanka President form a new front with UNP to contest parliamentary elections|url=http://www.colombopage.com/archive_15B/Jul11_1436599440CH.php|work=Colombo Page|date=11 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Rajasingham|first1=K. T.|title=A Broad Holy Alliance for Good Governance \u2013 Minus Maithripala Srisena|url=http://www.asiantribune.com/node/87334|work=[[Asian Tribune]]|date=12 July 2015}}</ref> Gunawardana did not contest the [[2015 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2015 parliamentary election]] but was instead placed on the UNFGG's list of [[National List Member of Parliament|National List]] candidates.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2015/PDF/Jul/1923_02/1923_02%28E%29.pdf|date=13 July 2015|title=PART I : SECTION (I) \u2014 GENERAL Government Notifications PARLIAMENTARY ELECTIONS ACT, No. 1 OF 1981 List of Persons submitted under Article 99A of the Constitution|journal=[[The Gazette of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka]] Extraordinary|volume=1923/02|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923223754/http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2015/PDF/Jul/1923_02/1923_02%28E%29.pdf|archivedate=23 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=UPFA, UNP national lists announced|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/79387/upfa-unp-national-lists-announced|work=[[The Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)]]|date=13 July 2015}}</ref> Gunawardana and other SLFP members, who accepted nominations by the UNFGG in response to former President [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]] being granted SLFP nomination to contest the election, had their SLFP membership suspended by President Sirisena, who had become leader of the SLFP and UPFA following the presidential election.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ariyawansha|first1=Niranjala|title=MS suspends SLFP Dissidents|url=http://www.ceylontoday.lk/51-99512-news-detail-ms-suspends-slfp-dissidents.html|work=[[Ceylon Today]]|date=29 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129061303/http://www.ceylontoday.lk/51-99512-news-detail-ms-suspends-slfp-dissidents.html|archivedate=29 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Santiago|first1=Melanie|title=Breaking: SLFP membership of Rajitha Senaratne and four others suspended|url=http://newsfirst.lk/english/2015/07/breaking-slfp-membership-of-rajitha-senaratne-and-four-others-suspended/105405|work=[[News First]]|date=28 July 2015}}</ref> They subsequently joined the Democratic National Movement.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Edirisinghe|first1=Dasun|title=DNM demands vacant UNP seat|url=http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=138992|work=[[The Island (Sri Lanka)]]|date=22 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Gooneratne |first1=Lankesh |title=Ekanayake scotches rumours |url=http://www.ceylontoday.lk/51-116880-news-detail-ekanayake-scotches-rumours.html |work=[[Ceylon Today]] |date=2 February 2016 }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Gunawardana was appointed as a UNFGG National List MP following the parliamentary election in August 2015.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2015/PDF/Aug/1928_25/1928_25%20E.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923223732/http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2015/PDF/Aug/1928_25/1928_25%20E.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 September 2015 |date=21 August 2015 |title=PART I : SECTION (I) \u2014 GENERAL Government Notifications PARLIAMENTARY ELECTION \u2014 2015 Declaration under Article 99A of the Constitution |journal=[[The Gazette of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka]] Extraordinary |volume=1928/25 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=UNP national list|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/84249/unp-national-list-submitted-to-ec|work=[[The Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)]]|date=21 August 2015}}</ref> He was re-appointed Minister of Lands after the parliamentary election.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2015/PDF/Sep/1932_07/1932_07%20E.pdf |date=14 September 2015 |title=PART I : SECTION (I) \u2014 GENERAL Appointments & c., by the President |journal=[[The Gazette of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka]] Extraordinary |volume=1932/07 }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=New Cabinet|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/86047/new-cabinet|work=[[The Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)]]|date=4 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The new Cabinet |url=http://www.ceylontoday.lk/16-102824-news-detail-the-new-cabinet.html |work=[[Ceylon Today]] |date=4 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907020713/http://www.ceylontoday.lk/16-102824-news-detail-the-new-cabinet.html |archivedate=7 September 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn late 2015 Gunawardana travelled to the United Kingdom, where his daughter and son live, for medical treatment, staying with his daughter in [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]].<ref>{{cite news|title=MKDS is in good health|url=http://www.hirunews.lk/121735/mkds-in-good-health|work=Hiru News|date=10 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=LeN200116>{{cite news|title=M.K.D.S. Gunawardena -Another stalwart who came forward come what may to support good governance passes away|url=http://lankaenews.com/news/1064/en|work=Lanka-e-News|date=20 January 2016}}</ref> On 11 December 2015 Parliament granted Gunawardana three months leave of absence for health reasons.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Parliamentary Debates: Official Report|journal=Hansard|date=11 December 2015|volume=241|issue=8|page=1482|url=http://www.parliament.lk/uploads/documents/hansard/1450325269057843.pdf|publisher=[[Parliament of Sri Lanka]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Parliament approves leave for ailing Minister|url=http://www.ceylontoday.lk/16-112025-news-detail-parliament-approves-leave-for-ailing-minister.html|work=[[Ceylon Today]]|date=11 December 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129081340/http://www.ceylontoday.lk/16-112025-news-detail-parliament-approves-leave-for-ailing-minister.html|archivedate=29 January 2016}}</ref> Gunawardana returned to Sri Lanka but his condition deteriorated.<ref name=LeN200116/> Gunawardana died at a private hospital in [[Colombo]] on 19 January 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Riza|first1=Shaahidah|title=M.K.D.S. no more|url=https://www.ceylontoday.lk/51-115667-news-detail-mkds-no-more.html|work=[[Ceylon Today]]|date=20 January 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129060437/https://www.ceylontoday.lk/51-115667-news-detail-mkds-no-more.html|archivedate=29 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Minister M.K.A.D.S Gunawardana passes away|url=http://nation.lk/online/2016/01/19/26713/|work=[[The Nation (Sri Lanka)]]|date=19 January 2016|access-date=23 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204023745/http://nation.lk/online/2016/01/19/26713/|archive-date=4 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hirunews.lk/124342/mkds-gunawardenas-last-rites-to-be-held-in-kanthale \n|title=MKDS Gunawardena\u2019s last rites to be held in Kanthale|work=Hiru News}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|+ Electoral history of M. K. A. D. S. Gunawardana\n! scope=col|Election\n! scope=col|Constituency\n! scope=col|Party\n! scope=col|Votes\n! scope=col|Result\n|-\n| [[1989 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|1989 parliamentary]]<ref name=pe89/> || [[Trincomalee Electoral District|Trincomalee District]] || [[Sri Lanka Freedom Party|SLFP]] || align=right|{{Nts|11260}} || '''Elected'''\n|-\n| [[1994 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|1994 parliamentary]] || [[Trincomalee Electoral District|Trincomalee District]] || [[People's Alliance (Sri Lanka)|PA]] ||  || Not elected\n|-\n| [[2000 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2000 parliamentary]]<ref name=pe00/> || [[Trincomalee Electoral District|Trincomalee District]] || [[People's Alliance (Sri Lanka)|PA]] || align=right|{{Nts|15392}} || '''Elected'''\n|-\n| [[2001 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2001 parliamentary]]<ref name=pe01/> || [[Trincomalee Electoral District|Trincomalee District]] || [[People's Alliance (Sri Lanka)|PA]] || align=right|{{Nts|14938}} || '''Elected'''\n|-\n| [[2004 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2004 parliamentary]]<ref name=pe04/> || [[Trincomalee Electoral District|Trincomalee District]] || [[United People's Freedom Alliance|UPFA]] || align=right|{{Nts|15060}} || Not elected\n|-\n| [[Sri Lanka Provincial Council elections, 2008\u20132009|2008 provincial]] || [[Trincomalee Electoral District|Trincomalee District]] || [[United People's Freedom Alliance|UPFA]] ||  || '''Elected'''\n|-\n| [[2010 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2010 parliamentary]]<ref name=pe10/> ||[[Trincomalee Electoral District|Trincomalee District]] || [[United People's Freedom Alliance|UPFA]] || align=right|{{Nts|19734}} || '''Elected'''\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Members of the 9th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of the 11th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of the 12th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of the 14th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of the 15th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gunawardana, M. K. A. D. S.}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:Cabinet ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Deputy ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 9th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 11th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 12th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 14th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 15th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the Eastern Provincial Council]]\n[[Category:People from Eastern Province, Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese civil servants]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese politicians]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese police officers]]\n[[Category:Sri Lanka Freedom Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:United People's Freedom Alliance politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix   = [[The Honourable|Hon.]]\n|name               = M. K. A. D. S. Gunawardana\n|native_name        = \n|native_name_lang   = \n|honorific-suffix   = \n|image              = M. K. D. S. Gunawardena.jpg\n|imagesize          =\n|caption            = Gunawardana in May 2014\n|office1            = [[Minister of Lands (Sri Lanka)|Minister of Lands]]\n|president1             = [[Maithripala Sirisena]]\n|primeminister1      = [[Ranil Wickremesinghe]]\n|predecessor1       = [[Janaka Bandara Tennakoon]]\n|successor1         = [[John Amaratunga]]\n|term_start1        = 12 January 2015\n|term_end1          = 19 January 2016\n|office2            = [[Ministry of Buddha Sasana|Deputy Minister of Buddha Sasana and Religious Affairs]]\n|president2             = [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]]\n|primeminister2      = [[D. M. Jayaratne]]\n|predecessor2       = \n|successor2         = [[Tissa Karalliyadde]]\n|term_start2        = 22 November 2010\n|term_end2          = 21 November 2014\n|constituency_MP3   = [[National List Member of Parliament|National List]]\n|parliament3        = Sri Lankan\n|term_start3        = 2015\n|term_end3          = 19 January 2016\n|predecessor3       = \n|successor3         = [[Sarath Fonseka]]\n|constituency_MP4   = [[Trincomalee Electoral District|Trincomalee District]]\n|parliament4        = Sri Lankan\n|term_start4        = 2010\n|term_end4          = 26 June 2015\n|predecessor4       = \n|successor4         = \n|term_start5        = 2000\n|term_end5          = 7 February 2004\n|predecessor5       = \n|successor5         = \n|term_start6        = 1989\n|term_end6          = 24 June 1994\n|predecessor6       = \n|successor6         = \n|office7            = Member of the [[Eastern Provincial Council]] for [[Trincomalee Electoral District|Trincomalee District]]\n|term_start7        = 2008\n|term_end7          = 2010\n|predecessor7       = \n|successor7         = N. G. Hewawitharana\n|birth_date         = {{Birth date|1947|03|06|df=yes}}\n|birth_place        = \n|death_date         = {{Death date and age|2016|01|19|1947|03|06|df=yes}}\n|death_place        = [[Colombo]], Sri Lanka\n|citizenship        =\n|nationality        = \n|party              = Democratic National Movement\n|otherparty         = [[United National Front for Good Governance]]\n|spouse             = \n|partner            = \n|relations          = \n|children           =\n|residence          = \n|alma_mater         = \n|occupation         = \n|profession         = \n|religion           = [[Buddhism in Sri Lanka|Buddhist]]\n|website            =\n|footnotes          =\n|blank1             = Ethnicity\n|data1              = [[Sinhalese people|Sinhalese]]\n}}\n'''Munasinghe Kariyawasam Appuhamilage Don Somadasa Gunawardana''' (6 March 1947 \u2013 19 January 2016) was a [[Sri Lanka]]n politician and a former member of Parliament and government minister.\n\n==Early life==\nGunawardana was born 6 March 1947.<ref>{{cite web|title=Directory of Members: M. K. A. D. S. Gunawardana|url=http://www.parliament.lk/en/members-of-parliament/directory-of-members/viewMember/87|publisher=[[Parliament of Sri Lanka]]}}</ref><ref name=deSilva>{{cite book|last1=de Silva |first1=W. P. P. |last2=Ferdinando |first2=T. C. L. |title=9th Parliament of Sri Lanka |publisher=[[Associated Newspapers of Ceylon Limited]] |page=273 |url=http://noolaham.net/project/148/14715/14715.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150623233447/http://noolaham.net/project/148/14715/14715.pdf |archivedate=2015-06-23 }}</ref> He was educated at Doranagoda Maha Vidyalaya.<ref name=NF200116>{{cite news|last1=Santiago|first1=Melanie|title=Final rites of late Minister M.K.A.D.S.Gunawardena to take place|url=http://newsfirst.lk/english/2016/01/final-rites-of-late-minister-m-k-a-d-s-gunawardena-to-take-place/125580|work=[[News First]]|date=20 January 2016}}</ref> After completing his [[GCE Ordinary Level in Sri Lanka|GCE Ordinary Level]] education he obtained a certificate in agriculture.<ref name=deSilva/>\n\n==Career==\nGunawardana was an overseer at the Land Commissioner's Department from 1966 to 1968 when he joined the [[Sri Lanka Police Service|police]] as a [[constable]].<ref name=deSilva/><ref name=ST040508>{{cite news|title=The people are grateful to the UPFA|url=http://www.sundaytimes.lk/080504/News/news0030.html|work=[[The Sunday Times (Sri Lanka)]]|date=4 May 2008}}</ref> He was a police investigator between 1974 and 1984.<ref name=deSilva/> He had reached the rank of [[Assistant Superintendent of Police]] by the time he retired.<ref name=NF200116/> During the [[1987\u201389 JVP insurrection|second JVP insurrection]] Gunawardana was arrested for \"anti-government activities\" and detained between September 1987 and May 1988.<ref name=deSilva/>\n\nGunawardana joined the [[Sri Lanka Freedom Party]] (SLFP) and in 1982 became active in politics.<ref name=NF200116/> He was the SLFP's organiser for the Seruvila electorate.<ref>{{cite news|title=Battle for SLFP leadership postponed to May|url=http://www.thesundayleader.lk/archive/20060409/news.htm|work=[[The Sunday Leader]]|date=9 April 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Jathika Saviya compensates Muttur Muslims|url=http://archives.dailynews.lk/2006/09/26/news18.asp|work=[[Daily News (Sri Lanka)]]|date=26 September 2006}}</ref> He contested the [[1989 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|1989 parliamentary election]] as one of the SLFP's candidates in [[Trincomalee Electoral District|Trincomalee District]]. He was elected and entered [[Parliament of Sri Lanka|Parliament]].<ref name=pe89>{{cite web |url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/Results_1989%20GENERAL%20ELECTION.PDF |archive-url=https://wayback.archive-it.org/all/20090304101343/http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/Results_1989%20GENERAL%20ELECTION.PDF |url-status=dead |archive-date=2009-03-04 |title=Result of Parliamentary General Election 1989 |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka }}</ref> In 1993 the SLFP and United Socialist Alliance formed the [[People's Alliance (Sri Lanka)|People's Alliance]] (PA).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Peebles|first1=Patrick|title=Historical Dictionary of Sri Lanka|date=2015|publisher=[[Rowman & Littlefield]]|isbn=978-1-4422-5584-5|page=267|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=50igCgAAQBAJ}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=East|first1=Roger|last2=Thomas|first2=Richard J.|title=Profiles of People in Power: The World's Government Leaders|date=2003|publisher=[[Europa Publications]]|isbn=1-85743-126-X|page=[https://archive.org/details/profilesofpeople0001east/page/486 486]|url=https://archive.org/details/profilesofpeople0001east|url-access=registration}}</ref> Gunawardana was one of the PA's candidates in Trincomalee District at the [[1994 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|1994 parliamentary election]] but the PA failed to win any seats in the district.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/Results_1994%20GENERAL%20ELECTION-SM01.PDF |title=Result of Parliamentary General Election 1994 |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101006015411/http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/Results_1994%20GENERAL%20ELECTION-SM01.PDF |archivedate=2010-10-06 }}</ref><ref name=TN250498>{{cite news|title=Eastern colonisation ongoing- UNP|url=http://www.tamilnet.com/art.html?catid=13&artid=1344|work=[[TamilNet]]|date=25 April 1998}}</ref> Gunawardana organised [[Sri Lankan state-sponsored colonisation schemes|illegal colonisation]] in the [[Kantalai]] area.<ref name=TN250498/> Gunawardana was one of the PA's candidates in Trincomalee District at the [[2000 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2000 parliamentary election]]. He was elected and re-entered Parliament.<ref name=pe00>{{cite web|url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/preference2000GE.PDF |title=General Election 2000 Preferences |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826002922/http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/preference2000GE.PDF |archivedate=2010-08-26 }}</ref> He was re-elected at the [[2001 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2001 parliamentary election]].<ref name=pe01>{{cite web|url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/preference2001GE.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100304015155/http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/preference2001GE.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-03-04 |title=General Election 2001 Preferences |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka }}</ref>\n\nOn 20 January 2004 the SLFP and the [[Janatha Vimukthi Peramuna]] formed the [[United People's Freedom Alliance]] (UPFA).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tamilnet.com/art.html?catid=13&artid=11003|title=SLFP-JVP alliance signed in Colombo|date=20 January 2004|publisher=[[TamilNet]]}}</ref> Gunawardana was one of the UPFA's candidates in Trincomalee District at the [[2004 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2004 parliamentary election]] but failed to get re-elected after coming second amongst the UPFA candidates.<ref name=pe04>{{cite web|url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/Preference2004GE.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100304015514/http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/Preference2004GE.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-03-04 |title=General Election 2004 Preferences |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka }}</ref> Gunawardana contested the [[Sri Lankan provincial council elections, 2008\u201309|2008 provincial council election]] as one of the UPFA's candidates in Trincomalee District and was elected to the [[Eastern Provincial Council]] (EPC).<ref name=ST040508/><ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2008/pdf/May/1549_17/1549_17E.pdf |date=15 May 2008 |title=PART I : SECTION (I) \u2014 GENERAL Government Notifications PROVINCIAL COUNCILS ELECTIONS ACT, No. 2 OF 1988 Eastern Province Provincial Council |journal=[[The Gazette of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka]] Extraordinary |volume=1549/17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525195143/http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2008/pdf/May/1549_17/1549_17E.pdf |archivedate=25 May 2014 }}</ref> He was elected deputy chairman of EPC unopposed on 4 June 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=UNP, SLMC councilors boycott EPC first sitting|url=http://www.tamilnet.com/art.html?catid=13&artid=25888|newspaper=[[TamilNet]]|date=5 June 2008}}</ref>\n\nGunawardana contested the [[2010 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2010 parliamentary election]] as one of the UPFA's candidates in Trincomalee District. He was elected and re-entered Parliament.<ref name=pe10>{{cite web|url=http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/GE2010_preferences/Trincomalee_pref_GE2010.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100513034918/http://www.slelections.gov.lk/pdf/GE2010_preferences/Trincomalee_pref_GE2010.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=2010-05-13 |title=Parliamentary General Election - 2010 Trincomalee Preferences |publisher=Department of Elections, Sri Lanka }}</ref> He was appointed Deputy Minister of Buddha Sasana and Religious Affairs in November 2010.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2010/PDF/Nov/1681_02/1681_02%20(E).pdf|date=22 November 2010|title=PART I : SECTION (I) \u2014 GENERAL Appointments & c., by the President|journal=[[The Gazette of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka]] Extraordinary|volume=1681/2|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140222024545/http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2010/PDF/Nov/1681_02/1681_02%20%28E%29.pdf|archivedate=22 February 2014}}</ref> Gunawardana was hospitalised in July 2012 following a minor heart attack at his home in Kantalai.<ref>{{cite news|title=Deputy Minister hospitalized|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/19511/deputy-minister-hospitalized|work=[[The Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)]]|date=18 June 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Dy. Minister in ICU|url=http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=54787|work=[[The Island (Sri Lanka)]]|date=19 June 2012}}</ref>\n\nGunawardana left the UPFA in November 2014 to support common opposition candidate [[Maithripala Sirisena]] at the [[2015 Sri Lankan presidential election|2015 presidential election]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Maithripala named common candidate |url=http://www.nation.lk/edition/latest-top-stories/item/35382-maithripala-named-common-candidate.html |work=[[The Nation (Sri Lanka)]] |date=21 November 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141129040752/http://www.nation.lk/edition/latest-top-stories/item/35382-maithripala-named-common-candidate.html |archivedate=29 November 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Dalima|first1=Bella|title=I am the common candidate: Maithripala Sirisena|url=http://newsfirst.lk/english/2014/11/common-candidate-maithripala-sirisena/63900|work=[[News First]]|date=21 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Chandrika, Rajitha, Arjuna, Rajeeva, M K D S and Dumindha Dissanayaka join Maithripala|url=http://www.hirunews.lk/goldfmnews/97592/chandrika-rajitha-arjuna-rajeeva-m-k-d-s-dumindha-dissanayaka-join-maithripala|work=Hiru News|date=21 November 2014|access-date=23 January 2016|archive-url=https://archive.today/20141121210910/http://www.hirunews.lk/goldfmnews/97592/chandrika-rajitha-arjuna-rajeeva-m-k-d-s-dumindha-dissanayaka-join-maithripala|archive-date=21 November 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Gunawardana and other SLFP MPs who supported Sirisena were stripped of their ministerial positions and expelled from the SLFP.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2014/PDF/Nov/1890_14/1890_14%20E.pdf|date=26 November 2014|title=PART I : SECTION (I) \u2014 GENERAL Government Notifications NOTIFICATION|journal=[[The Gazette of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka]] Extraordinary|volume=1890/14|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128115159/http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2014/PDF/Nov/1890_14/1890_14%20E.pdf|archivedate=28 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=SLFP rebels stripped of posts and party membership|url=http://www.nation.lk/edition/breaking-news/item/35387-slfp-rebels-stripped-of-posts-and-party-membership.html|work=[[The Nation (Sri Lanka)]]|date=21 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150125124038/http://www.nation.lk/edition/breaking-news/item/35387-slfp-rebels-stripped-of-posts-and-party-membership.html|archivedate=25 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sri Lanka Presidential Election Set for January 8 Next Year|url=http://www.ndtv.com/article/world/sri-lanka-presidential-election-set-for-january-8-next-year-624180|work=[[NDTV]]|agency=[[Press Trust of India]]|date=21 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Maithripala and others sacked|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/57117/maithripala-and-others-sacked|work=[[The Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)]]|date=21 November 2014}}</ref> After the election newly elected [[President of Sri Lanka|President]] Sirisena rewarded Gunawardana by appointing him [[Minister of Lands (Sri Lanka)|Minister of Lands]].<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2015/PDF/Jan/1897_16/1897_16%20%28E%29.pdf|date=18 January 2015|title=PART I : SECTION (I) \u2014 GENERAL Appointments & c., by the President|journal=[[The Gazette of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka]] Extraordinary|volume=1897/16|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150128115111/http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2015/PDF/Jan/1897_16/1897_16%20%28E%29.pdf|archivedate=28 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=New Cabinet ministers sworn in|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/61073/new-cabinet-ministers-sworn-in|work=[[The Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)]]|date=12 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=New Cabinet takes oaths |url=http://www.nation.lk/edition/latest-top-stories/item/37306-new-cabinet-takes-oaths.html |work=[[The Nation (Sri Lanka)]] |date=12 January 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150118145912/http://www.nation.lk/edition/latest-top-stories/item/37306-new-cabinet-takes-oaths.html |archivedate=18 January 2015 }}</ref> Gunawardana became a vice president of the SLFP in February 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Paranamanna|first1=Lakna|title=Susil appointed as national organizer of SLFP|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/63669/rajitha-v-president-susil-national-organizer-of-slfp|work=[[The Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)]]|date=14 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=SLFP appoints new National Organiser, Treasurer and VP|url=http://www.adaderana.lk/news/29803/slfp-appoints-new-national-organiser-treasurer-and-vp|work=adaderana.lk|date=14 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2015 Gunawardana and other supporters of President Sirisena formed the [[United National Front for Good Governance]] (UNFGG) to contest the [[2015 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|parliamentary election]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Perera|first1=Yohan|title=Good Governance MoU signed|url=http://mirrorcitizen.dailymirror.lk/2015/07/13/good-governance-mou-signed/|work=[[The Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)]]|date=13 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Disillusioned supporters of Sri Lanka President form a new front with UNP to contest parliamentary elections|url=http://www.colombopage.com/archive_15B/Jul11_1436599440CH.php|work=Colombo Page|date=11 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Rajasingham|first1=K. T.|title=A Broad Holy Alliance for Good Governance \u2013 Minus Maithripala Srisena|url=http://www.asiantribune.com/node/87334|work=[[Asian Tribune]]|date=12 July 2015}}</ref> Gunawardana did not contest the [[2015 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2015 parliamentary election]] but was instead placed on the UNFGG's list of [[National List Member of Parliament|National List]] candidates.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2015/PDF/Jul/1923_02/1923_02%28E%29.pdf|date=13 July 2015|title=PART I : SECTION (I) \u2014 GENERAL Government Notifications PARLIAMENTARY ELECTIONS ACT, No. 1 OF 1981 List of Persons submitted under Article 99A of the Constitution|journal=[[The Gazette of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka]] Extraordinary|volume=1923/02|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923223754/http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2015/PDF/Jul/1923_02/1923_02%28E%29.pdf|archivedate=23 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=UPFA, UNP national lists announced|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/79387/upfa-unp-national-lists-announced|work=[[The Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)]]|date=13 July 2015}}</ref> Gunawardana and other SLFP members, who accepted nominations by the UNFGG in response to former President [[Mahinda Rajapaksa]] being granted SLFP nomination to contest the election, had their SLFP membership suspended by President Sirisena, who had become leader of the SLFP and UPFA following the presidential election.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ariyawansha|first1=Niranjala|title=MS suspends SLFP Dissidents|url=http://www.ceylontoday.lk/51-99512-news-detail-ms-suspends-slfp-dissidents.html|work=[[Ceylon Today]]|date=29 July 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129061303/http://www.ceylontoday.lk/51-99512-news-detail-ms-suspends-slfp-dissidents.html|archivedate=29 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Santiago|first1=Melanie|title=Breaking: SLFP membership of Rajitha Senaratne and four others suspended|url=http://newsfirst.lk/english/2015/07/breaking-slfp-membership-of-rajitha-senaratne-and-four-others-suspended/105405|work=[[News First]]|date=28 July 2015}}</ref> They subsequently joined the Democratic National Movement.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Edirisinghe|first1=Dasun|title=DNM demands vacant UNP seat|url=http://www.island.lk/index.php?page_cat=article-details&page=article-details&code_title=138992|work=[[The Island (Sri Lanka)]]|date=22 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Gooneratne |first1=Lankesh |title=Ekanayake scotches rumours |url=http://www.ceylontoday.lk/51-116880-news-detail-ekanayake-scotches-rumours.html |work=[[Ceylon Today]] |date=2 February 2016 }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Gunawardana was appointed as a UNFGG National List MP following the parliamentary election in August 2015.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2015/PDF/Aug/1928_25/1928_25%20E.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923223732/http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2015/PDF/Aug/1928_25/1928_25%20E.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=23 September 2015 |date=21 August 2015 |title=PART I : SECTION (I) \u2014 GENERAL Government Notifications PARLIAMENTARY ELECTION \u2014 2015 Declaration under Article 99A of the Constitution |journal=[[The Gazette of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka]] Extraordinary |volume=1928/25 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=UNP national list|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/84249/unp-national-list-submitted-to-ec|work=[[The Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)]]|date=21 August 2015}}</ref> He was re-appointed Minister of Lands after the parliamentary election.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://www.documents.gov.lk/Extgzt/2015/PDF/Sep/1932_07/1932_07%20E.pdf |date=14 September 2015 |title=PART I : SECTION (I) \u2014 GENERAL Appointments & c., by the President |journal=[[The Gazette of the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka]] Extraordinary |volume=1932/07 }}{{dead link|date=May 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=New Cabinet|url=http://www.dailymirror.lk/86047/new-cabinet|work=[[The Daily Mirror (Sri Lanka)]]|date=4 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=The new Cabinet |url=http://www.ceylontoday.lk/16-102824-news-detail-the-new-cabinet.html |work=[[Ceylon Today]] |date=4 September 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907020713/http://www.ceylontoday.lk/16-102824-news-detail-the-new-cabinet.html |archivedate=7 September 2015 }}</ref>\n\nIn late 2015 Gunawardana travelled to the United Kingdom, where his daughter and son live, for medical treatment, staying with his daughter in [[Reading, Berkshire|Reading]].<ref>{{cite news|title=MKDS is in good health|url=http://www.hirunews.lk/121735/mkds-in-good-health|work=Hiru News|date=10 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=LeN200116>{{cite news|title=M.K.D.S. Gunawardena -Another stalwart who came forward come what may to support good governance passes away|url=http://lankaenews.com/news/1064/en|work=Lanka-e-News|date=20 January 2016}}</ref> On 11 December 2015 Parliament granted Gunawardana three months leave of absence for health reasons.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Parliamentary Debates: Official Report|journal=Hansard|date=11 December 2015|volume=241|issue=8|page=1482|url=http://www.parliament.lk/uploads/documents/hansard/1450325269057843.pdf|publisher=[[Parliament of Sri Lanka]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Parliament approves leave for ailing Minister|url=http://www.ceylontoday.lk/16-112025-news-detail-parliament-approves-leave-for-ailing-minister.html|work=[[Ceylon Today]]|date=11 December 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129081340/http://www.ceylontoday.lk/16-112025-news-detail-parliament-approves-leave-for-ailing-minister.html|archivedate=29 January 2016}}</ref> Gunawardana returned to Sri Lanka but his condition deteriorated.<ref name=LeN200116/> Gunawardana died at a private hospital in [[Colombo]] on 19 January 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Riza|first1=Shaahidah|title=M.K.D.S. no more|url=https://www.ceylontoday.lk/51-115667-news-detail-mkds-no-more.html|work=[[Ceylon Today]]|date=20 January 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160129060437/https://www.ceylontoday.lk/51-115667-news-detail-mkds-no-more.html|archivedate=29 January 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Minister M.K.A.D.S Gunawardana passes away|url=http://nation.lk/online/2016/01/19/26713/|work=[[The Nation (Sri Lanka)]]|date=19 January 2016|access-date=23 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204023745/http://nation.lk/online/2016/01/19/26713/|archive-date=4 February 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hirunews.lk/124342/mkds-gunawardenas-last-rites-to-be-held-in-kanthale \n|title=MKDS Gunawardena\u2019s last rites to be held in Kanthale|work=Hiru News}}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left;\"\n|+ Electoral history of M. K. A. D. S. Gunawardana\n! scope=col|Election\n! scope=col|Constituency\n! scope=col|Party\n! scope=col|Votes\n! scope=col|Result\n|-\n| [[1989 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|1989 parliamentary]]<ref name=pe89/> || [[Trincomalee Electoral District|Trincomalee District]] || [[Sri Lanka Freedom Party|SLFP]] || align=right|{{Nts|11260}} || '''Elected'''\n|-\n| [[1994 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|1994 parliamentary]] || [[Trincomalee Electoral District|Trincomalee District]] || [[People's Alliance (Sri Lanka)|PA]] ||  || Not elected\n|-\n| [[2000 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2000 parliamentary]]<ref name=pe00/> || [[Trincomalee Electoral District|Trincomalee District]] || [[People's Alliance (Sri Lanka)|PA]] || align=right|{{Nts|15392}} || '''Elected'''\n|-\n| [[2001 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2001 parliamentary]]<ref name=pe01/> || [[Trincomalee Electoral District|Trincomalee District]] || [[People's Alliance (Sri Lanka)|PA]] || align=right|{{Nts|14938}} || '''Elected'''\n|-\n| [[2004 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2004 parliamentary]]<ref name=pe04/> || [[Trincomalee Electoral District|Trincomalee District]] || [[United People's Freedom Alliance|UPFA]] || align=right|{{Nts|15060}} || Not elected\n|-\n| [[Sri Lanka Provincial Council elections, 2008\u20132009|2008 provincial]] || [[Trincomalee Electoral District|Trincomalee District]] || [[United People's Freedom Alliance|UPFA]] ||  || '''Elected'''\n|-\n| [[2010 Sri Lankan parliamentary election|2010 parliamentary]]<ref name=pe10/> ||[[Trincomalee Electoral District|Trincomalee District]] || [[United People's Freedom Alliance|UPFA]] || align=right|{{Nts|19734}} || '''Elected'''\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Members of the 9th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of the 11th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of the 12th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of the 14th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n{{Members of the 15th Parliament of Sri Lanka}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gunawardana, M. K. A. D. S.}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:2016 deaths]]\n[[Category:Cabinet ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Deputy ministers of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 9th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 11th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 12th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 14th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the 15th Parliament of Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Members of the Eastern Provincial Council]]\n[[Category:People from Eastern Province, Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese civil servants]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese politicians]]\n[[Category:Sinhalese police officers]]\n[[Category:Sri Lanka Freedom Party politicians]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:United People's Freedom Alliance politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Prasa niro", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M._K._A._D._S._Gunawardana"}
{"title_page": "Drifting (1923 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|1923 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Drifting\n| image          = Drifting (1923) poster.jpg\n| caption        = Poster for ''Drifting''\n| director       = [[Tod Browning]]\n| producer       = [[Carl Laemmle]]\n| writer         = Tod Browning<br>[[A. P. Younger]]\n| based on       = {{basedon|''Drifting'' (play)|[[John Colton (screenwriter)|John Colton]]<br>Daisy H. Andrews}} \n| starring       = [[Priscilla Dean]]<br>[[Matt Moore (actor)|Matt Moore]]<br>[[Wallace Beery]]\n| cinematography = William Fildew\n| editing        = [[Errol Taggart]]\n| distributor    = [[Universal Studios|Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{film date|1923|8|26}}\n| runtime        = 70 minutes\n| country        = United States \n| language       = [[Silent film|Silent]]<br>[[Intertitle]]s by Gardner Bradford\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Drifting''''' is a 1923 American silent [[drama film]] based on the play ''Drifting'', by [[John Colton (screenwriter)|John Colton]] and Daisy H. Andrews. The film was directed by [[Tod Browning]] and features [[Priscilla Dean]], [[Wallace Beery]] and [[Anna May Wong]]. It was produced and distributed by [[Universal Pictures]].<ref name=\"silentera\">{{cite web |url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/D/Drifting1923.html |title=Progressive Silent Film List: ''Drifting'' |accessdate=June 5, 2008|work=Silent Era}}</ref> Copies of the film exist in Moscow and in the [[George Eastman House Motion Picture Collection]].<ref name=\"LOC\">{{cite web |url=http://lcweb2.loc.gov/diglib/ihas/loc.mbrs.sfdb.1572/default.html |title=Drifting  |accessdate=January 9, 2014 |work=American Silent Feature Film Survival Database}}</ref> In 2012 the [[National Film Preservation Foundation]] awarded a grant to preserve a print that has Czech language [[intertitles]] which were translated back into English.<ref>{{cite press release\n | title = NATIONAL FILM PRESERVATION FOUNDATION AWARDS 35 PRESERVATION GRANTS\n | publisher = National Film Preservation Foundation\n | date = June 12, 2012\n | url = http://www.filmpreservation.org/about/PR-2012-06-12\n | accessdate = March 12, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | title = Film Preservation Fridays #4: Title and Intertitle Re-creation \n | publisher = SF Silent Film Festival Blog \n | date = June 17, 2011\n | url = http://sfsilentfilmfestival.blogspot.com/2011/06/film-preservation-fridays-4-title-and.html\n | accessdate = March 12, 2015\n}}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nCassie Cook had played the opium selling game until fate and a bad shuffle compelled her to team up with her biggest rival, Jules Repin, and then the horror of the whole thing weighed down upon her and she determined to quit and leave China before it was too late. She had bought a lot of new gowns on credit, believing in Repin's promise that he had a big shipment of opium coming in which would give them both plenty of money. Now those gowns had to be paid for and Cassie's chum, Molly Morton, taken out of the country before a growing taste for opium got a final hold on her. So Cassie bet on a sure thing in the races and lost. \"But I'm going to get you out, Kid,\" she told Molly, and as a last resort she went back to the game. Up in Hang Chow, a trouble-infested village near the poppy fields, she tried to trace the shipment Repin expected. A white man was there \u2014 supposed to be opening an abandoned mine. It was her business to find out if he was a government inspector seeking the den of the dope dealers. She posed as a novelist, and he, believing in her, told her that he was there to fight the dope menace. Cassie felt like a cheat of the lowest order and she turned against her comrades, but they, by trickery, found out what she had learned from the mine superintendent. In a flash they set the little world ablaze with rebellion and the soul of Cassie Cook was cleansed in the fires of remorse as she battled for what she believed was the right cause, and out of it came a love that was clean and honorable.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Priscilla Dean]] as Cassie Cook / Lucille Preston\n* [[Matt Moore (actor)|Matt Moore]] as Capt. Arthur Jarvis\n* [[Wallace Beery]] as Jules Repin\n* [[J. Farrell MacDonald]] as Murphy\n* [[Rose Dione]] as Madame Polly Voo\n* [[Edna Tichenor]] as Molly Norton\n* [[William V. Mong]] as Dr. Li\n* [[Anna May Wong]] as Rose Li\n* [[Bruce Guerin]] as Billy Hepburn\n* Marie De Albert as Mrs. Hepburn\n* William F. Moran as Mr. Hepburn\n* [[Frank Lanning]] as Chang Wang\n\n==See also==\n* [[Anna May Wong filmography]]\n* [[List of American films of 1923]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Drifting (1923 film)}}\n*{{IMDb title|0014003|Drifting}}\n*{{AllRovi movie|90038|Drifting}}\n\n{{Tod Browning |state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:1923 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American silent feature films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:1923 drama films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Tod Browning]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American films based on plays]]\n[[Category:Films set in China]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|1923 film}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Drifting\n| image          = Drifting (1923) poster.jpg\n| caption        = Poster for ''Drifting''\n| director       = [[Tod Browning]]\n| producer       = [[Carl Laemmle]]\n| writer         = Tod Browning<br>[[A. P. Younger]]\n| based on       = {{basedon|''Drifting'' (play)|[[John Colton (screenwriter)|John Colton]]<br>Daisy H. Andrews}} \n| starring       = [[Priscilla Dean]]<br>[[Matt Moore (actor)|Matt Moore]]<br>[[Wallace Beery]]\n| cinematography = William Fildew\n| editing        = [[Errol Taggart]]\n| distributor    = [[Universal Studios|Universal Pictures]]\n| released       = {{film date|1923|8|26}}\n| runtime        = 70 minutes\n| country        = United States \n| language       = [[Silent film|Silent]]<br>[[Intertitle]]s by Gardner Bradford\n| budget         = \n}}\n\n'''''Drifting''''' is a 1923 American silent [[drama film]] based on the play ''Drifting'', by [[John Colton (screenwriter)|John Colton]] and Daisy H. Andrews. The film was directed by [[Tod Browning]] and features [[Priscilla Dean]], [[Wallace Beery]] and [[Anna May Wong]]. It was produced and distributed by [[Universal Pictures]].<ref name=\"silentera\">{{cite web |url=http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/D/Drifting1923.html |title=Progressive Silent Film List: ''Drifting'' |accessdate=June 5, 2008|work=Silent Era}}</ref> Copies of the film exist in Moscow and in the [[George Eastman House Motion Picture Collection]].<ref name=\"LOC\">{{cite web |url=http://lcweb2.loc.gov/diglib/ihas/loc.mbrs.sfdb.1572/default.html |title=Drifting  |accessdate=January 9, 2014 |work=American Silent Feature Film Survival Database}}</ref> In 2012 the [[National Film Preservation Foundation]] awarded a grant to preserve a print that has Czech language [[intertitles]] which were translated back into English.<ref>{{cite press release\n | title = NATIONAL FILM PRESERVATION FOUNDATION AWARDS 35 PRESERVATION GRANTS\n | publisher = National Film Preservation Foundation\n | date = June 12, 2012\n | url = http://www.filmpreservation.org/about/PR-2012-06-12\n | accessdate = March 12, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | title = Film Preservation Fridays #4: Title and Intertitle Re-creation \n | publisher = SF Silent Film Festival Blog \n | date = June 17, 2011\n | url = http://sfsilentfilmfestival.blogspot.com/2011/06/film-preservation-fridays-4-title-and.html\n | accessdate = March 12, 2015\n}}</ref>\n\n==Synopsis==\nCassie Cook had played the opium selling game until fate and a bad shuffle compelled her to team up with her biggest rival, Jules Repin, and then the horror of the whole thing weighed down upon her and she determined to quit and leave China before it was too late. She had bought a lot of new gowns on credit, believing in Repin's promise that he had a big shipment of opium coming in which would give them both plenty of money. Now those gowns had to be paid for and Cassie's chum, Molly Morton, taken out of the country before a growing taste for opium got a final hold on her. So Cassie bet on a sure thing in the races and lost. \"But I'm going to get you out, Kid,\" she told Molly, and as a last resort she went back to the game. Up in Hang Chow, a trouble-infested village near the poppy fields, she tried to trace the shipment Repin expected. A white man was there \u2014 supposed to be opening an abandoned mine. It was her business to find out if he was a government inspector seeking the den of the dope dealers. She posed as a novelist, and he, believing in her, told her that he was there to fight the dope menace. Cassie felt like a cheat of the lowest order and she turned against her comrades, but they, by trickery, found out what she had learned from the mine superintendent. In a flash they set the little world ablaze with rebellion and the soul of Cassie Cook was cleansed in the fires of remorse as she battled for what she believed was the right cause, and out of it came a love that was clean and honorable.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Priscilla Dean]] as Cassie Cook / Lucille Preston\n* [[Matt Moore (actor)|Matt Moore]] as Capt. Arthur Jarvis\n* [[Wallace Beery]] as Jules Repin\n* [[J. Farrell MacDonald]] as Murphy\n* [[Rose Dione]] as Madame Polly Voo\n* [[Edna Tichenor]] as Molly Norton\n* [[William V. Mong]] as Dr. Li\n* [[Anna May Wong]] as Rose Li\n* [[Bruce Guerin]] as Billy Hepburn\n* Marie De Albert as Mrs. Hepburn\n* William F. Moran as Mr. Hepburn\n* [[Frank Lanning]] as Chang Wang\n\n==See also==\n* [[Anna May Wong filmography]]\n* [[List of American films of 1923]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Drifting (1923 film)}}\n*{{IMDb title|0014003|Drifting}}\n*{{AllRovi movie|90038|Drifting}}\n\n{{Tod Browning |state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:1923 films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American silent feature films]]\n[[Category:American black-and-white films]]\n[[Category:1923 drama films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Tod Browning]]\n[[Category:Universal Pictures films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American films based on plays]]\n[[Category:Films set in China]]\n", "name_user": "Lugnuts", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drifting_(1923_film)"}
{"title_page": "Ron Cooper (American football)", "text_new": "{{short description|American football coach}}\n{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Ron Cooper\n| image = \n| alt = \n| caption = \n| current_title = Defensive backs coach\n| current_team = [[Arkansas Razorbacks football|Arkansas]]\n| current_conference = [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]]\n| current_record = \n| contract = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1962|2|11}}\n| birth_place = [[Huntsville, Alabama]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = \n| player_years1 = 1979\u20131982\n| player_team1 = [[Jacksonville State Gamecocks football|Jacksonville State]]\n| coach_years1 = 1983\n| coach_team1 = [[Appalachian State Mountaineers football|Appalachian State]] ([[Graduate assistant|GA]])\n| coach_years2 = 1984\n| coach_team2 = [[Minnesota Golden Gophers football|Minnesota]] (GA)\n| coach_years3 = 1985\u20131986\n| coach_team3 = [[Austin Peay Governors football|Austin Peay]] (assistant)\n| coach_years4 = 1987\u20131988\n| coach_team4 = [[Murray State Racers football|Murray State]] (DC)\n| coach_years5 = 1989\n| coach_team5 = [[East Carolina Pirates football|East Carolina]] (assistant)\n| coach_years6 = 1990\n| coach_team6 = [[UNLV Rebels football|UNLV]] (DC)\n| coach_years7 = 1991\u20131992\n| coach_team7 = [[Notre Dame Fighting Irish football|Notre Dame]] (assistant)\n| coach_years8 = 1993\u20131994\n| coach_team8 = [[Eastern Michigan Eagles football|Eastern Michigan]]\n| coach_years9 = 1995\u20131997\n| coach_team9 = [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville]]\n| coach_years10 = 1998\u20132001\n| coach_team10 = [[Alabama A&M Bulldogs football|Alabama A&M]]\n| coach_years11 = 2002\n| coach_team11 = [[Wisconsin Badgers football|Wisconsin]] (DB)\n| coach_years12 = 2003\n| coach_team12 = [[Mississippi State Bulldogs football|Mississippi State]] (DC)\n| coach_years13 = 2004\n| coach_team13 = [[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]] (DB)\n| coach_years14 = 2005\n| coach_team14 = [[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]] (OLB/ST)\n| coach_years15 = 2006\u20132007\n| coach_team15 = [[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]] (AHC/DB)\n| coach_years16 = 2008\n| coach_team16 = [[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]] (S)\n| coach_years17 = 2009\u20132011\n| coach_team17 = [[LSU Tigers football|LSU]] (DB)\n| coach_years18 = 2012\n| coach_team18 = [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] (DB)\n| coach_years19 = 2013\u20132014\n| coach_team19 = [[South Florida Bulls football|South Florida]] (AHC/DB)\n| coach_years20 = 2015\n| coach_team20 = [[FIU Panthers football|FIU]] (DB)\n| coach_years21 = 2016\n| coach_team21 = [[FIU Panthers football|FIU]] (DC/LB)\n| coach_years22 = 2016\n| coach_team22 = [[FIU Panthers football|FIU]] (interim)\n| coach_years23 = 2017\n| coach_team23 = [[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M]] (DB)\n| coach_years24 = 2018\u2013present\n| coach_team24 = [[Arkansas Razorbacks football|Arkansas]] (DB) \n| overall_record = 49\u201359\n| bowl_record = \n| tournament_record = \n| championships = \n| awards = 1 [[Southwest Athletic Conference|SWAC Eastern Division]] (2000)\n| coaching_records = \n}}\n\n'''Ronald Louis Cooper''' (born February 11, 1962) is an [[American football]] coach and former player. Currently, Cooper is the defensive backs coach at [[Arkansas Razorbacks football|Arkansas]]. Cooper served as the head football coach at [[Eastern Michigan University]] (1993\u20131994), the [[University of Louisville]] (1995\u20131997), [[Alabama Agricultural and Mechanical University|Alabama A&M]] (1998\u20132001), and the interim head coach at [[Florida International University|FIU]] (2016). He was the defensive backs coach for the [[Tampa Bay Buccaneers]] in 2012. A native of [[Huntsville, Alabama]], he played [[high school football]] at [[Lee High School (Huntsville, Alabama)|Lee High School]] and [[college football]] at [[Jacksonville State University]].<ref name=\"hsvt120108\">{{cite news |first=Mark |last=McCarter |newspaper=[[The Huntsville Times]] |location=[[Huntsville, AL]] |publisher=[[Advance Publications]] |title=Ron Cooper's path to LSU and BCS title game began on fringe of Alabama A&M campus |url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2012/01/ron_coopers_path_to_lsu_and_bc.html |date=January 8, 2012 |accessdate=December 5, 2013 |quote=Cooper played high school football at Lee, then played for Jacksonville State.}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\n===Eastern Michigan===\nCooper was the head football coach at [[Eastern Michigan University]] in [[Ypsilanti, Michigan]] from 1993 to 1994. At Eastern Michigan, his teams produced a record of 9\u201313.<ref>[http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/div_ia/mac/eastern_michigan/coaching_records.php College Football Data Warehouse] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101205035939/http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/div_ia/mac/eastern_michigan/coaching_records.php |date=2010-12-05 }} Eastern Michigan all time coaching records</ref>\n\n===Louisville===\nFrom 1995 to 1997 Cooper was the head football coach at the [[University of Louisville]], replacing [[Howard Schnellenberger]]. In his final season, the Cardinals posted a 1\u201310 record. The one win came against Illinois who finished the season with no wins (0\u201311). Cooper's overall record at Louisville was 13\u201320.<ref>[http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/div_ia/bigeast/louisville/coaching_records.php College Football Data Warehouse] Louisville all time coaching records</ref> On November 19, 1997, Louisville fired Cooper due to a steady decline in the team's performance.<ref>{{cite web|author=Story, Mark|title=U of L drops Cooper as coach, citing 'negativity'|work=Lexington Herald-Leader|date=November 20, 1997|url=http://www.kentuckyconnect.com/heraldleader/news/112097/fcooper.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20000601033338/http://www.kentuckyconnect.com/heraldleader/news/112097/fcooper.html|archivedate=June 1, 2000|accessdate=July 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Alabama A&M===\nCooper's last head coaching position was at [[Alabama Agricultural and Mechanical University]], from 1998 to 2001. His squad won a division championship in [[Southwest Athletic Conference]] (SWAC) during the 2000 season<ref>[http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/div_iaa/southwestern/alabama_a&m/coaching_records.php College Football Data Warehouse] Alabama A&M all time coaching records</ref> but lost the [[SWAC Championship Game]] to [[Grambling]] on December 12, 2000.<ref>[http://www.cfbdatawarehouse.com/data/coaching/alltime_coach_game_by_game.php?coachid=441&year=2000 College Football Data Warehouse] Alabama A&M 2000 season results</ref>\n\n===Other coaching duties===\nIn 2002, Cooper was the secondaries coach at the [[University of Wisconsin\u2013Madison]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamecocksonline.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/cooper_ron00.html|title=GamecocksOnline.com  - South Carolina Gamecocks Official Athletic Site Official Athletic Site of the South Carolina Gamecocks - Football|publisher=}}</ref> and in 2003 the defensive coordinator and safeties coach at [[Mississippi State]]. Other coaching stops have included the [[University of South Carolina]] and the [[University of Notre Dame]]. Cooper is an alumnus of [[Jacksonville State University]].\n\n===Tampa Bay Buccaneers===\nCooper was hired by the Buccaneers on February 22, 2012 to be the team's defensive backs coach.\n\n===Florida International===\nIn 2015, Cooper became the defensive coordinator and associate head coach at [[Florida International University]]. Following [[Ron Turner (American football)|Ron Turner]]'s termination in September 2016, Cooper was named interim head coach.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fiusports.com/news/2016/9/25/football-ron-turner-relieved-of-duties.aspx |title=Ron Turner Relieved of Duties |publisher=FIU Sports |date= September 25, 2016 |accessdate=September 25, 2016 }}</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = 