{"title_page": "Roderick Jones (1877\u20131962)", "text_new": "{{For|others of the same name|Roderick Jones}}\nSir '''George Roderick Jones''' (21 October 1877 \u2013 23 January 1962) was a British journalist and news agency manager, who for most of his career worked for [[Reuters]]. From 1916, he was a significant shareholder in the company.\n\n==Life==\nJones was born in [[Dukinfield]], [[Cheshire]], the only son of Roderick Patrick Jones, a hat salesman, working in [[Manchester]], by his marriage to Christina Drennan Gibb.<ref name=odnb>[https://doi.org/10.1093/ref:odnb/34227 Jones, Sir (George) Roderick (1877\u20131962), news agency director], in [[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]] online, accessed 15 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref> In 1895, Jones went out to South Africa, where he worked as a journalist and in 1905 became general manager of the Reuters office.<ref name=palmer>Michael B. Palmer, ''International News Agencies: A History'', p. 75</ref> \n\nIn April 1915, during the [[World War I|First World War]], the Reuters general manager in London, Baron de Reuter, killed himself, soon after his son had joined the British Army and his wife had died. In October 1915, Jones was appointed as general manager, and in 1916 he and the company chairman, Mark Napier, bought the company, with financial help from the British government.<ref name=palmer/> During the rest of the War, Reuters followed a carefully patriotic line, so much so that Jones was accused of being the British government's Head of Propaganda. He was knighted in 1918, in recognition of his services to journalism.<ref name=odnb/>\n\nJones became chairman of Reuters, as well as general manager, and retired from those posts in 1941.<ref name=odnb/> In 1951, [[Hodder & Stoughton]] published his autobiography ''A Life in Reuters''.<ref>Roderick Jones, ''A Life in Reuters'' (Hodder & Stoughton, 1951), {{ISBN|978-1125911136}}</ref>\n\nJones had a house at 29 [[Hyde Park Gate]], [[Westminster]], where he died on 23 January 1962, and he was buried at [[Rottingdean]], where he also had a home, North End House, previously owned by the artist [[Edward Burne-Jones]].<ref name=odnb/> He left an estate valued at \u00a338,042, and probate was granted on 14 May to his daughter Laurian, Comtesse d\u2019Harcourt, wife of Comte Anne-Pierre d\u2019Harcourt.<ref>\u201cJONES sir George Roderick otherwise Sir Roderick K.B.E.\u201d in Probate Index for 1962, at probatesearch.service.gov.uk, accessed 15 April 2020</ref>\n\nThe [[National Portrait Gallery, London|National Portrait Gallery]] has portrait photographs of Jones by [[Alexander Bassano|Bassano]] and [[Walter Stoneman]].<ref>[https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp78568/sir-george-roderick-jones Sir (George) Roderick Jones (1877-1962)] at [[National Portrait Gallery, London]], accessed 17 April 2020</ref>\n\n==Family==\nIn 1920, Jones married the author [[Enid Bagnold]], and they had four children.<ref name=odnb/> Their only daughter, Laurian, was briefly married, from 1952 to 1955, to [[Rowland Winn, 4th Baron St Oswald|Rowland Winn]].<ref>[http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/stoswald1885.htm Saint Oswald, Baron (UK, 1885)] at cracroftspeerage.co.uk, accessed 18 April 2020</ref> Their son Timothy Angus Jones married Patricia David Pandora Clifford, daughter of [[Bede Clifford|Sir Bede Clifford]],<ref>''[[Burke's Peerage]]'', vol. 1 (1999), p. 131</ref> and was the father of [[Annabel Astor, Viscountess Astor|Annabel Astor]], the mother of [[Samantha Cameron]].<ref>Melonie Clarke, Helena Gumley-Mason, \u201dSamantha Cameron's Sari Diplomacy\u201d in ''[[The Lady (magazine)|The Lady]]'', 26 November 2013, [https://web.archive.org/web/20140525195032/http://www.lady.co.uk/people/profiles/3336-samantha-cameron-s-sari-diplomacy archived here]</ref> Their son Richard Bagnold Jones was a writer on [[narrow-gauge railways]].<ref>[https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp67753/richard-bagnold-jones Richard Bagnold Jones] at [[National Gallery, London]], accessed 18 April 2020</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n==Further reading==\n*[[Donald Read]], \u201dSir Roderick Jones and Reuters: Rise and Fall of a News Emperor\u201d, in D. Fraser, ed., ''Cities, Class and Communications, Essays in Honour of Asa Briggs'' (Harvester, 1990), pp. 175-99\n* Roderick Jones, ''A Life in Reuters'' (Hodder & Stoughton, 1951) {{ISBN|978-1125911136}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.thebaron.info/archives/sir-roderick-joness-finest-hour Sir Roderick Jones\u2019s Finest Hour] at thebaron.info\n*[https://www.worldcat.org/identities/viaf-93722307/ Jones, Roderick Sir 1877-1962] at worldcat.org\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Roderick}}\n[[Category:1877 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:People from Dukinfield]]\n[[Category:Reuters people]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|others of the same name|Roderick Jones}}\nSir '''George Roderick Jones''' (21 October 1877 \u2013 23 January 1962) was a British journalist and news agency manager, who for most of his career worked for [[Reuters]]. From 1916, he was a significant shareholder in the company.\n\n==Life==\nJones was born in [[Dukinfield]], [[Cheshire]], the only son of Roderick Patrick Jones, a hat salesman, working in [[Manchester]], by his marriage to Christina Drennan Gibb.<ref name=odnb>[https://doi.org/10.1093/ref:odnb/34227 Jones, Sir (George) Roderick (1877\u20131962), news agency director], in [[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]] online, accessed 15 April 2020 {{subscription}}</ref> In 1895, Jones went out to South Africa, where he worked as a journalist and in 1905 became general manager of the Reuters office.<ref name=palmer>Michael B. Palmer, ''International News Agencies: A History'', p. 75</ref> \n\nIn April 1915, during the [[World War I|First World War]], the Reuters general manager in London, Baron de Reuter, killed himself, soon after his son had joined the British Army and his wife had died. In October 1915, Jones was appointed as general manager, and in 1916 he and the company chairman, Mark Napier, bought the company, with financial help from the British government.<ref name=palmer/> During the rest of the War, Reuters followed a carefully patriotic line, so much so that Jones was accused of being the British government's Head of Propaganda. He was knighted in 1918, in recognition of his services to journalism.<ref name=odnb/>\n\nJones became chairman of Reuters, as well as general manager, and retired from those posts in 1941.<ref name=odnb/> In 1951, [[Hodder & Stoughton]] published his autobiography ''A Life in Reuters''.<ref>Roderick Jones, ''A Life in Reuters'' (Hodder & Stoughton, 1951), {{ISBN|978-1125911136}}</ref>\n\nJones had a house at 29 [[Hyde Park Gate]], [[Westminster]], where he died on 23 January 1962, and he was buried at [[Rottingdean]], where he also had a home, North End House, previously owned by the artist [[Edward Burne-Jones]].<ref name=odnb/> He left an estate valued at \u00a338,042, and probate was granted on 14 May to his daughter Laurian, Comtesse d\u2019Harcourt, wife of Comte Anne-Pierre d\u2019Harcourt.<ref>\u201cJONES sir George Roderick otherwise Sir Roderick K.B.E.\u201d in Probate Index for 1962, at probatesearch.service.gov.uk, accessed 15 April 2020</ref>\n\nThe [[National Portrait Gallery, London|National Portrait Gallery]] has portrait photographs of Jones by [[Alexander Bassano|Bassano]] and [[Walter Stoneman]].<ref>[https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp78568/sir-george-roderick-jones Sir (George) Roderick Jones (1877-1962)] at [[National Portrait Gallery, London]], accessed 17 April 2020</ref>\n\n==Family==\nIn 1920, Jones married the author [[Enid Bagnold]], and they had four children.<ref name=odnb/> Their only daughter, Laurian, was briefly married, from 1952 to 1955, to [[Rowland Winn, 4th Baron St Oswald|Rowland Winn]].<ref>[http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/stoswald1885.htm Saint Oswald, Baron (UK, 1885)] at cracroftspeerage.co.uk, accessed 18 April 2020</ref> Their son Timothy Angus Jones married Patricia David Pandora Clifford, daughter of [[Bede Clifford|Sir Bede Clifford]],<ref>''Burke's Peerage]]'', vol. 1 (1999), p. 131</ref> and was the father of [[Annabel Astor, Viscountess Astor|Annabel Astor]], the mother of [[Samantha Cameron]].<ref>Melonie Clarke, Helena Gumley-Mason, \u201dSamantha Cameron's Sari Diplomacy\u201d in ''[[The Lady (magazine)|The Lady]]'', 26 November 2013, [https://web.archive.org/web/20140525195032/http://www.lady.co.uk/people/profiles/3336-samantha-cameron-s-sari-diplomacy archived here]</ref> Their son Richard Bagnold Jones was a writer on [[narrow-gauge railways]].<ref>[https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp67753/richard-bagnold-jones Richard Bagnold Jones] at [[National Gallery, London]], accessed 18 April 2020</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n==Further reading==\n*[[Donald Read]], \u201dSir Roderick Jones and Reuters: Rise and Fall of a News Emperor\u201d, in D. Fraser, ed., ''Cities, Class and Communications, Essays in Honour of Asa Briggs'' (Harvester, 1990), pp. 175-99\n* Roderick Jones, ''A Life in Reuters'' (Hodder & Stoughton, 1951) {{ISBN|978-1125911136}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.thebaron.info/archives/sir-roderick-joness-finest-hour Sir Roderick Jones\u2019s Finest Hour] at thebaron.info\n*[https://www.worldcat.org/identities/viaf-93722307/ Jones, Roderick Sir 1877-1962] at worldcat.org\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Roderick}}\n[[Category:1877 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:People from Dukinfield]]\n[[Category:Reuters people]]\n", "name_user": "Moonraker", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFamily", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Roderick_Jones_(1877%E2%80%931962)"}
